{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: failure is at module handoff to API client (payload fields can be dropped between builder and caller), so Unit is too low. REAL-INFRA: no OS/network behavior is required; a stub client that captures outbound payload is sufficient, so System is rejected by behavior text 'request sent ... includes ... labels' (payload-shape check only). LLM-DEP/MULTI-STEP: no dependence on model judgment and no multi-step agent pipeline, so Agentic/Workflow are disqualified.","test_description":"Wire classifier module to an in-process fake API client that records requests; call classify() and assert the outbound request contains every configured taxonomy label exactly once.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: this is response-handoff behavior across API adapter + normalization + public return path; a pure Unit test on mapper can miss wiring defects. REAL-INFRA: real network is unnecessary; deterministic fake API response reproduces the failure boundary, so System is rejected by text 'When the API returns a label...' (single response mapping). LLM-DEP/MULTI-STEP: correctness is deterministic normalization, not model quality or chained agent decisions.","test_description":"Use an in-process fake provider returning an out-of-taxonomy label; invoke classify() and assert returned value is exactly 'unknown'.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.06,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"For identical raw API responses, the module's normalization step always produces the same final label.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: behavior is explicitly one local normalization function/object ('normalization step') with identical input -> identical output; no module handoff is required. REAL-INFRA/LLM-DEP/MULTI-STEP: no OS/network/subprocess, no real model call, no chained agentic stages. Higher levels are disqualified by behavior text 'identical raw API responses' focusing on deterministic local transform.","test_description":"Call normalization with the same raw provider payload many times and assert the normalized label is stable and identical across runs.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"On repeated live API calls for the same document and taxonomy, the returned label remains consistent unless the provider response itself changes.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Behavior text explicitly requires 'repeated live API calls' and consistency conditional on provider output changes. LLM-DEP: execution depends on real model/provider outputs and possible non-determinism; stubs would hide real drift/variance failures. Integration is rejected because fake responses cannot expose live-model variability. Workflow is rejected because this is one agentic decision repeated, not multiple distinct agentic stages in sequence.","test_description":"Run N real provider calls with identical document+taxonomy; for each call capture raw provider label and module-returned label. Assert module return is consistent whenever raw provider label is unchanged, and only differs when raw provider label differs.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.16,"Agentic":0.75,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Request construction enforces the configured token budget before dispatch (for example truncate/reject according to policy).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: real failure often occurs at boundary between token-budget logic and dispatch gate (e.g., policy computed but not enforced), so Unit-only parser/math tests are insufficient. REAL-INFRA: no need for real provider/network; fake client can verify dispatch blocked or truncated payload, so System is disqualified by 'before dispatch'. LLM-DEP/MULTI-STEP: no dependence on model output quality and no multi-step agent chain.","test_description":"Configure a low budget, send oversized document, and use a fake API client to assert policy behavior: either request is truncated to budgeted tokens before send or send is rejected with no API call, per configured policy.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Provider-reported token usage for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"This requires real provider-reported usage; a mock can always claim in-budget and hide true provider tokenization/usage behavior. Because execution path uses a real AI API call and assertion depends on provider output metadata, Agentic is the safer minimum. Integration is rejected: behavior text 'Provider-reported token usage' disqualifies stub-only validation. Workflow is rejected because it is a single call check, not multi-stage agentic sequencing.","test_description":"Execute classification against the real provider for a representative document and taxonomy, read provider token_usage fields, and assert reported total tokens <= configured budget (with fixed test inputs/config).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.22,"Agentic":0.67,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: failure is in orchestration between API adapter, retry policy, and wait/backoff handling; needs module wiring. REAL-INFRA: deterministic fake provider responses (429 then success) plus controllable clock/timer can reproduce behavior; real network timing is not required, so System is rejected. LLM-DEP/MULTI-STEP: correctness is retry control flow, not model output quality, and no multi-agent pipeline.","test_description":"Use a fake provider scripted to return rate-limit error then success; invoke classify() and assert module performs delay/backoff + retry attempts and eventually returns success instead of bubbling the first error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.76,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.02}}]}
